```python
from typing import List


def filter_by_substring(strings: List[str], substring: str) -> List[str]:
    return [s for s in strings if substring in s]
```

Note: The provided solution uses list comprehension, which is an efficient and pythonic way to filter the list based on the given condition.

The `in` operator is used to check if the `substring` is present in the `strings` element. If it is, the element is included in the new list that is returned.

This solution has a time complexity of O(n*m), where n is the length of the input list and m is the length of the substring. This is because in the worst case, Python needs to check each character in the substring against every character in the string.

This solution has a space complexity of O(n), where n is the length of the input list. This is because in the worst case, all elements in the input list are included in the output list.

This solution is efficient for large lists and substrings, as it makes only a single pass through the input list. However, if the substring is very long compared to the strings in the list, the overall time complexity can be high. In such cases, more sophisticated algorithms that take advantage of the properties of the strings and substrings could be considered. However, this is beyond the scope of this implementation.

